layable characters of the game are in the Acorn Plains world. Mario is jumping on Yoshi as they look to the camera. Luigi with a shocked expression is holding onto a Balloon Baby Yoshi trying to avoid a Piranha Plant. Blue Toad is holding onto a bubble-blowing Baby Yoshi as it blows bubbles and traps a Goomba inside. Yellow Toad is flying while wearing the Flying Squirrel Suit. The game's logo appears below.\n| developer = [[Nintendo EAD]]\n| publisher = [[Nintendo]] (Worldwide)<br>[[Tencent Games]] (China, Deluxe only)\n| director = Masataka Takemoto\n| producer = {{ubl|[[Takashi Tezuka]]|[[Hiroyuki Kimura]]}}\n| designer = {{ubl|Shigeyuki Asuke|Daiki Iwamoto|Ryutaro Kanno}}\n| programmer = \n| artist = Masanobu Sato\n| writer = \n| composer = {{ubl|Shiho Fujii|[[Mahito Yokota]]}}\n| series = ''[[Super Mario]]''\n| engine = \n| platforms = [[Wii U]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = '''Wii U'''{{Video game release|NA|November 18, 2012|PAL|November 30, 2012|JP|December 8, 2012}}'''Nintendo Switch''' {{Video game release|WW|January 11, 2019}} {{Video game release|China|December 10, 2019}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo foot|'''''New Super Mario Bros. U'''''|New \u30b9\u30fc\u30d1\u30fc\u30de\u30ea\u30aa\u30d6\u30e9\u30b6\u30fc\u30ba U|Ny\u016b S\u016bp\u0101 Mario Buraz\u0101zu Y\u016b|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[2.5D]] [[side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[platform video game]] developed and published in 2012 by [[Nintendo]] as a [[launch game|launch title]] for the [[Wii U]]. It is the fourth title in the ''[[New Super Mario Bros. (series)|New Super Mario Bros. series]]''.<ref name=\"nintendolife\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2012/06/first_impressions_new_super_mario_bros_u |title=First Impressions: New Super Mario Bros. U |date=June 19, 2012 |last=Newton |first=James |publisher=NintendoLife |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622051426/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2012/06/first_impressions_new_super_mario_bros_u |archive-date=2012-06-22 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> An additional campaign for the ''Year of Luigi'', ''[[New Super Luigi U]]'', was released as [[downloadable content]] in June 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2013/02/14/nintendo-announces-new-super-luigi-u-dlc-announced|title=Nintendo Announces New Super Luigi U DLC|last=Karmali|first=Luke|date=2013-02-14|website=IGN|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> A standalone retail version was released the following month.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/new-super-luigi-u-gets-a-full-retail-release-august-25-508193346 |title=New Super Luigi U Gets A Full Retail Release August 25 |publisher=Kotaku.com |accessdate=June 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607225809/http://kotaku.com/new-super-luigi-u-gets-a-full-retail-release-august-25-508193346 |archive-date=2013-06-07 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> The game received positive reviews, and is one of the [[List of best-selling Wii U video games|best-selling games on the Wii U]] and [[List of best-selling Nintendo Switch video games|Nintendo Switch]].\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Princess Peach]] is held captive in her castle by [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]], Bowser Jr., and the [[Koopalings]] who invade and use a giant mechanical arm to throw [[Mario]], [[Luigi]], and two [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]]s far away. Mario and friends must now travel across this new land returning to Peach's castle in order to save her. On the way, they encounter seven Koopalings each controlling their own worlds, plus [[Kamek]], Nabbit, Bowser Jr., and many minor monsters like [[Goomba]]. By conquering them, they get closer to Peach's castle, which has been transformed into an evil reflection of Bowser. By defeating Bowser, the castle returns to normal. As the heroes celebrate, Bowser Jr. and the Koopalings attempt to escape, almost leaving Bowser behind. He manages to jump up onto the airship, but his weight causes it to crash, and they are forced to flee on Bowser Jr.'s Koopa Clown Car.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:Wii U with stylus at Igromir 2013 (10096264706).jpg|thumb|left|Players can use the Wii U GamePad's stylus to add platforms and stun enemies on the main screen.]]\n\n''New Super Mario Bros. U'' iterates on the gameplay featured in ''[[New Super Mario Bros. Wii]]''. The objective of each [[Level (video gaming)|level]] is to reach the goal flag at the end of each level while avoiding enemies and hazards.\n\nThe game can be controlled either using [[Wii Remote]]s or the [[Wii U GamePad]], the latter of which allows for [[Off-TV Play]], where the game can be played solely on the GamePad's screen, without the use of a television.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-9020_7-57552003-222/what-the-wii-u-needs-next/ |title=What the Wii U needs next |first=Scott |last=Stein |date=November 19, 2012 |work=[[CNET]] |accessdate=December 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127194909/http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-9020_7-57552003-222/what-the-wii-u-needs-next/ |archive-date=2012-11-27 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> [[Wii U Pro Controller]] support was added in the 1.3.0 patch.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://mynintendonews.com/2013/06/20/new-super-mario-bros-u-update-allows-wii-u-pro-controller-use/|title=New Super Mario Bros. U Update Allows Wii U Pro Controller Use|date=June 20, 2013|accessdate=June 22, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622134148/http://mynintendonews.com/2013/06/20/new-super-mario-bros-u-update-allows-wii-u-pro-controller-use/|archive-date=2013-06-22|url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nUp to five players can play simultaneously. In multiplayer, the player using the Wii U GamePad cannot control a character, but instead can interact with the environment, such as putting blocks down that can aid Mario or stunning enemies. As such, in multiplayer, there must be an equal number of controllers, excluding the GamePad, to the desired number of on-screen characters.\n\nCertain game modes also allow players to play [[Mii]] characters saved on their console. New to this release is an asymmetric multiplayer experience called Boost Mode. In this mode, the player with the GamePad can aid other players by using the touchscreen to place blocks on the screen or stun enemies. This can be used to assist amateur players and to allow expert players to perform speed runs.<ref name=\"flying squirrel\"/>\n<ref name=\"gamerant\"/> The [[Koopalings]], [[Bowser (character)|Bowser]], [[Kamek]], Boom Boom, and [[Bowser Jr.]] appear as the game's main villains.\n\nAlong with returning elements, such as Ice Flowers and [[Yoshi]]s, ''New Super Mario Bros. U'' introduces new [[power-up]]s, such as a [[flying squirrel]] suit that allows players to glide across long distances or slowly descend down vertical paths<ref name=\"flying squirrel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/06/05/e3-2011-new-super-mario-bros-u-the-glory-of-the-flying-squirrel |title=E3 2012: New Super Mario Bros. U - The Glory of the Flying Squirrel |author=George, Richard |publisher=IGN |date=June 5, 2012 |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616135859/http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/06/05/e3-2011-new-super-mario-bros-u-the-glory-of-the-flying-squirrel |archive-date=2012-06-16 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> and cling to the side of the walls.<ref name=not>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.mobilenapps.com/articles/3097/20120714/new-super-mario-bros-u-launch-title.htm|title=New Super Mario Bros. U Not Launch Title or Rehash of Predecessors|publisher=Mobile & Apps|first=Jonathan|last=Charles|date=July 14, 2012|accessdate=September 24, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927042129/http://www.mobilenapps.com/articles/3097/20120714/new-super-mario-bros-u-launch-title.htm|archive-date=2016-09-27|url-status=live}}\n</ref> Baby Yoshis can be carried by the individual players. Each baby Yoshi has a special ability based on its color, such as inflating in midair, blowing bubbles to attack enemies and illuminating dark areas.<ref name=\"gamerant\">\n{{cite web |url=http://gamerant.com/new-super-mario-bros-u-handson-preview-riley-154118/ |title=\u2018New Super Mario Bros. U\u2019 Hands-On Preview |date=June 12, 2012 |last=Little |first=Riley |publisher=Game Rant, LLC |access-date=2012-06-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827131611/http://gamerant.com/new-super-mario-bros-u-handson-preview-riley-154118/ |archive-date=2012-08-27 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> Some older power-ups also have new abilities; for example, the Mini Mushroom now allows players to run up walls.<ref name=\"nindirect\" />\nUnlike the previous ''New Super Mario Bros.'' games, which have separate maps for each of the games' worlds, ''New Super Mario Bros. U'' features one large map containing all the game's worlds and levels, similar to that of ''[[Super Mario World]]''. Some levels have multiple exits that lead to the different areas on the map.<ref>{{cite web|author=Fletcher, Leon|title=Fab New Super Mario Bros. U Details Revealed|url=http://www.palmgamer.com/fab-new-super-mario-bros-u-details-revealed/|publisher=Palm Gamer|accessdate=September 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014101135/http://www.palmgamer.com/fab-new-super-mario-bros-u-details-revealed/|archive-date=October 14, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Super Guide, which takes control of the player's character and moves it automatically through a level, is available in case the player has failed a level many times.\n\nThe game features a new [[antagonist]] named Nabbit, who is chased after stealing a power-up from [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]]. Once Nabbit is caught, Toad rewards the item to the player.\n\nThe game features two new modes of play, Challenge Mode and Boost Rush. Challenge Mode adds unique challenges, such as clearing levels quickly or earning as many 1-UPs in a row as possible without touching the ground. The Coin Battles from ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'' also return and this time, the player can customize the battles with the GamePad to place the coins and Star Coins on the course.\n\nBoost Rush takes place on an automatically scrolling level which increases in speed as players collect coins, with the goal to clear the stage as quickly as possible.<ref name=\"nindirect\">\n{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5942967/its-impossible-to-hate-the-new-new-super-mario-bros-u |title=It's Impossible to Hate the New New Super Mario Bros. U |publisher=Kotaku.com |date=September 13, 2012 |accessdate=November 19, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119041527/http://kotaku.com/5942967/its-impossible-to-hate-the-new-new-super-mario-bros-u |archive-date=2012-11-19 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> The game originally utilized the now defunct [[Nintendo Network|Miiverse]], which allowed players to share comments about particular levels with one another.<ref name=not/>\n<ref name=\"tezuka1\">{{cite web |title=E3 2012: Behind the Scenes of New Super Mario Bros. U |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/06/05/e3-2012-behind-the-scenes-of-new-super-mario-bros-u |date=June 5, 2012 |last=George |first=Richard |publisher=IGN |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616012337/http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/06/05/e3-2012-behind-the-scenes-of-new-super-mario-bros-u |archive-date=2012-06-16 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n== Development ==\n''New Super Mario Bros. U'' started development shortly after the release of ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'' and took three years to develop.<ref name=\"Iwata asks 0.0\">\n{{cite web |work=Iwata Asks: New Super Mario Bros. U |title=What Should Be New? |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |publisher=[[Nintendo]] |url=http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wiiu/nsmbu/0/0 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927194716/http://iwataasks.nintendo.com/interviews/#/wiiu/nsmbu/0/0#/wiiu/nsmbu/0/0 |archive-date=2016-09-27 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> The game's soundtrack was written by Shiho Fujii and [[Mahito Yokota]], with series regular [[Koji Kondo]] serving as the sound advisor.\n\nThe game, initially titled ''New Super Mario Bros. Mii'', was first revealed at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2011|E3 2011]] as one of several [[Technology demonstration|tech demo]]s demonstrating the capabilities of [[Wii U]]. The demo's visual style duplicated ''New Super Mario Bros. Wii'', but featured [[High-definition video|high-definition]] graphics, and Mii characters were notably featured as playable characters alongside Mario and Luigi.<ref name=\"e32011\">\n{{cite web |url=http://wii.ign.com/articles/117/1174752p1.html |title=E3 2011: The Miis Meet Classic Nintendo Franchises on Wii U |date=June 8, 2011 |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |publisher=IGN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608065410/http://wii.ign.com/articles/117/1174752p1.html |archive-date=2012-06-08 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> [[Shigeru Miyamoto]] later announced that the ''Mario'' demo was going to be released as a full game for the system, and would be demonstrated in its revised form at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2012|E3 2012]].<ref>\n{{cite web |title=New Super Mario Bros. Mii Is the Mario Bros. Wii U Game |publisher=Nintendo World Report |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/29838 |date=April 16, 2012 |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |last=Dawson |first=James |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618170941/http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/29838 |archive-date=2012-06-18 |url-status=live }}\n</ref> The new game, titled ''New Super Mario Bros. U'', was revealed at the event and was announced to be released alongside the Wii U console.<ref name = \"nintendolife\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://kotaku.com/5915882/new-super-mario-bros-u-coming-to-wii-u |title=Hallelujah! ''New Super Mario Bros. U'' Coming to Wii U |date=June 5, 2012 |last=Narcisse |first=Evan |publisher=Kotaku |access-date=2012-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608033143/http://kotaku.com/5915882/new-super-mario-bros-u-coming-to-wii-u |archive-date=2012-06-08 |url-status=live }}\n</ref>\n\n== ''New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe'' ==\nIn the [[Nintendo Direct]] from September 14, 2018, Nintendo unveiled an enhanced port from ''New Super Mario Bros. U'' and ''New Super Luigi U'' exclusively for the [[Nintendo Switch]] titled ''New Super Mario Bros. U Deluxe''. The game contains ''New Super Mario Bros. U'' and ''New Super Luigi U'' and runs in [[1080p]] while the original Wii U version runs in [[720p]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/digitalfoundry-2019-new-super-mario-bros-u-deluxe-tech-analysis|title=How New Super Mario Bros U Deluxe on Switch improves over Wii U|last=Morgan|first=Thomas|date=2019-01-09|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>  Both versions of the game run at 60 [[Frame rate|frames per second]]. The game also contains a new playable character, [[Toadette]]. Nabbit also returns, after being exclusive from ''New Super Luigi U''. It was released on January 11, 2019. A power-up called the \"Super Crown\" is a power up exclusive for Toadette, which causes her to transform into a character that resembles Princess Peach, Peachette. As Peachette, she can float like Princess Peach and recover if she falls in pits or lava.{{citation needed |date=February 2020}}\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| state = plain\n| MC = (Wii U) 84/100<ref>\n{{cite web | title=New Super Mario Bros. U for Wii U Reviews | publisher=[[Metacritic]] | url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/new-super-mario-bros-u | accessdate=November 15, 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117025903/http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/new-super-mario-bros-u | archive-date=2012-11-17 | url-status=live }}\n</ref><br />(NS) 80/100<ref name=\"mc_ns_review\">\n{{cite web|title=New Super Mario Bros. U 